    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is Feline Stomatitis?</h2>
      <p>Feline chronic gingivostomatitis (FCGS) — commonly called stomatitis — is severe, painful inflammation of the mouth and gums. Cats with stomatitis often cannot eat comfortably, drop food, drool, or avoid hard food entirely. It significantly affects quality of life and is frequently misdiagnosed or undertreated as routine dental disease.</p>
      <p>Yams had stomatitis alongside CKD, dehydration, and hypertension — a combination that made his care particularly challenging, because treating the mouth pain was complicated by his kidney disease limiting some medication options.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="signs" class="content-section">
      <h2>Signs to Watch For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Reluctance to eat, especially hard food</li>
        <li>Dropping food from the mouth</li>
        <li>Excessive drooling, sometimes bloody</li>
        <li>Pawing at the mouth</li>
        <li>Bad breath beyond normal cat halitosis</li>
        <li>Weight loss due to pain-related food avoidance</li>
        <li>Behaviour changes — hiding, reduced grooming, irritability</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Stomatitis is painful.</strong> If your cat is showing signs of mouth discomfort, don't wait for the next routine appointment. This condition causes chronic pain that affects every aspect of daily life.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="treatment" class="content-section">
      <h2>Treatment</h2>
      <p>Stomatitis is caused by an abnormal immune response to plaque — the teeth themselves become triggers. This is why the most effective treatment is often aggressive.</p>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Full mouth extraction</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Removing all teeth eliminates the plaque triggers. Counterintuitively, most cats do remarkably well after full extraction — eating wet food without difficulty. It has the highest long-term success rate of any treatment. The idea sounds severe, but for many cats it is transformative.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Medical management</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Steroids, cyclosporine, and pain management can control symptoms in some cats. Often used while working toward surgery, or in cats where surgery is too high-risk. Long-term steroid use carries its own complications — kidney function should be monitored carefully.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Laser therapy</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Some cats respond to low-level laser therapy as an adjunct treatment. Not a standalone solution but can help manage inflammation alongside other approaches.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Is this stomatitis, or routine periodontal disease? How are you distinguishing them?</li>
        <li>What is my cat's pain level on a scale, and how are we managing it right now?</li>
        <li>Is my cat a candidate for full mouth extraction, and what is the success rate in your experience?</li>
        <li>If we pursue medical management, what are the long-term risks given my cat's kidney disease?</li>
        <li>How will we know if the current treatment is working?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

